          </caption>
          <graphic xlink:href="fmicb-09-01652-g007"/>
        </fig>
      </sec>
      <sec>
        <title>Correlation Between Colonic Microbial Composition and Inflammatory Cytokines-, Tight Junction Protein-, and Intestine Development-Related Gene Expression</title>
        <p>Pearson&#x2019;s correlation analysis showed that the gene expression of <italic>IL-6</italic> was positively associated with the abundance of <italic>Alloprevotella</italic>, but negatively related to the proportion of <italic>Clostridium sensu stricto</italic> in the colon (<bold>Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F8">8</xref></bold>). The gene expression of <italic>IL-18</italic> was positively correlated with the abundance of <italic>Bacteroides.</italic> The <italic>IL-10</italic> expression level was positively associated with the abundance of <italic>Parasutterella</italic>, but negatively related to the relative abundance of <italic>Alloprevotella.</italic> The <italic>TNF-&#x3B1;</italic> expression level was positively related to the abundance of <italic>Bacteroides</italic> and <italic>Phascolarctobacterium.</italic> The gene expression of <italic>HDAC1</italic> was positively correlated with the abundance of genera <italic>Alloprevotella</italic> and <italic>Blautia.</italic> The gene expression of occludin was positively correlated with the abundance of unclassified Clostridiales. The <italic>EGF</italic> expression level was negatively correlated with the abundance of <italic>Alloprevotella</italic> and <italic>Blautia</italic> in the colon.</p>
        <fig id="F8" position="float">
